Move the Secret:
    cp /home/botserver/ASP-site/.env /home/botserver/asp-site.env    
    chmod 600 /home/botserver/asp-site.env
Create the Web Root:
    sudo mkdir -p /var/www/asp-site/releases && sudo chown -R botserver:botserver /var/www/asp-site
Setup the Bare Repo:
    mkdir -p ~/repos/asp-site.git && cd ~/repos/asp-site.git && git init --bare
Copy the Hook:
    cp ~/scripts/post-receive ~/repos/asp-site.git/hooks/post-receive && chmod +x ~/repos/asp-site.git/hooks/post-receive
Copy the Service:
    cp ~/scripts/asp-site.service /etc/systemd/system/ && sudo systemctl daemon-reload && sudo systemctl enable asp-site.service
Add to Sudoers:
    sudo visudo and add: botserver ALL=(ALL) NOPASSWD: /usr/bin/systemctl restart asp-site.service
Windows Remote:
    git remote add production botserver@ip:repos/asp-site.git


Work: git checkout -b feature/new-ui -> Write code.
    Test on Dev:
    git checkout develop
    git merge feature/new-ui
    git push staging develop:main (This pushes your local develop branch to the server's main branch to trigger the build).
Deploy to Prod:
    git checkout main
    git merge develop
    git push production main

On your Staging server, you can set an environment variable in the .env file:
    ASPNETCORE_ENVIRONMENT=Staging
Your .NET code can then use this to:
    Use a different database (e.g., Games_Dev.db).
    Show a "BETA" ribbon on the website.
    Enable more verbose logging.

You could write a pre-receive hook that runs dotnet test. If the tests fail, the server rejects the push entirely.
    Your Windows terminal would show a big red error, and your server's files wouldn't even be touched.
